@Node UPDATE2 "Updating Searcher, v2.00 to Searcher, v2.01!"
Updating Searcher, v2.00 to v2.01:
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~

DON'T copy the following: !Puzzles, !Puzzles2, or ANY files in the Puzzles/
                          subdirectory.

   DO copy the following: ALL OTHER FILES located in this archive!

    OK, I lied, I want you to look in the "Puzzles/" subdirectory of this
archive and copy the four "BeanieBabies?" files into YOUR "Puzzles/" sub-
directory. These puzzles are correctly formatted, so as to be "sensed" the
next time the SysOp enters the program, so once copied, simply run Searcher
and it will add in these four puzzles!

    SysOps who may have noted that the SAVE command on the LOCAL side was
broken will be glad to note that it WORKS! hehe
@endnode
@Node UPDATE "Updating Searcher, v1.46 to Searcher, v2.00!"
Updating Searcher, v1.46 to v2.00:
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
DON'T copy the following: !Puzzles, !Puzzles2, or ANY files in the Puzzles/
                          subdirectory.

   DO copy the following: ALL OTHER FILES located in this archive, INCLUDING
                          the Update200 script.

    Run the included "Update200" script as a CNet ARexx door from WITHIN your
designated "/CNetSearcher/" path. This update will rename your puzzle files, as 
well as slightly changing your !Puzzles file, while moving it into the root 
"CNetSearcher/" directory. A second file, !Puzzles2, will also be created in 
your root "CNetSearcher/" directory.

    Upon completing the run of the "Update200" script, compare the files now
stored in YOUR "Puzzles/" directory to those stored in the "Puzzles/" directory
of this archive. Copy any NEW files from this directory INTO your "Puzzles/"
directory. When you run Searcher 2.00 for the first time, it will "sense" these
NEW puzzles and add them to the !Puzzles and !Puzzles2 files automatically.
@endnode
@Node INSTALL "How to Install CNet Amiga Searcher for the First Time!"
To Install:
~~~~~~~~~~~
    Copy the included "CNetSearcher/" directory somewhere on your system.
It doesn't matter WHERE you store this directory, so long as you keep ALL
files found WITHIN this directory inside the "CNetSearcher/" directory.

    This file was written and tested under CNet Amiga, v4.38, however it
should ALSO function perfectly using the 3.05c version too!

    You should now add the "<path>CNetSearcher/Searcher" program as an
ARexx Door file. You can opt to use the "AL" command to add it to one of
your list areas, or you can opt to add it as a command in CNet's BBSMENU
file. To do this, add the following line to the end of Menu # 2, the
Available Everywhere menu:

    WS, WordSearch  |  {#0<path>CNetSearcher/Searcher}
                       ^
                   Control-Q

    NOTE: Where "<path>" is the location you copied the "CNetSearcher/"
          directory to.

    At the START of the "Searcher" coding are numerous variables you may wish
to edit to customize how the program LOOKS and ACTS. Numerous of them deal
with the COLORS used within the program, while a NEW variable, SORT, allows
you to set the INITIAL sort order for the puzzles, however the USER can still
use the new "S"ort command to toggle the sorted display.

That's It!
@endnode
@Node PLAYING "Hints & Tips on Playing CNet Amiga Searcher!"
To Play the Game!
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
    This is another one of those fairly self explanatory games, where the
available keys will be shown to you at the start of the game.

    Each puzzle has the ability of maintaining a "champs" file, which will
list the last 15 players who successfully COMPLETED the puzzle. The data
found in these files is formatted this way:

    handle (?? wide ?? tall ?? dirs) in ?? hrs, ?? mins, ?? secs.

    The only piece of info here that might need further explanation is the
"dirs" value. This reflects the total number of directions that COULD have
been used to hide words, however it does NOT necessarily mean that ALL these
directions were used. Generally, the more directions the program can choose
to hide words from, the harder the game.

    When a user opts to QUIT the game, they'll be asked if they wish to
SAVE the game, so that they can choose to CONTINUE the game at a future
date and time. If a user CONTINUES a saved game, then SOLVES the game, the
saved game file will be deleted from the disk. A file "SearcherSav.#" will be
created in the user's mail directory. The # will be a digit from 0 to 9,
dependent on which Slot # they choose to store their game.
@endnode
@Node BUGS "Any known Bugs, Quirks, etc. in CNet Amiga Searcher?"
Known Bugs / Quirks?
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
    The new "SAVE GAME" feature does not take into consideration the length
of time it took the user to SOLVE the puzzle. Because of this, a check is
made to insure the user solved the puzzle in one sitting before being added
to the CHAMPS file. I had considered saving the "elapsed time so far" to
the saved game data file, but then considered the fact that the user could
get a hard copy of the screen, save the game, find all the words, then
resume the game only to blitzingly fast find all the words, so I opted to
NOT allow this to happen.

    If a user opts to quit the game before completing the entire word list,
they'll simply exit the game. NO ENTRY will be made to the "champs" file.
@endnode
@Node FUTURE "What's in the Future for CNet Amiga Searcher?"
In the future...
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
    Sometime in the future, I'd like to do the following:

- I'd also like to incorporate some form of POINT SCORE, based on WHICH
  directions were used, how many directions were used, whether HINTS were
  used, which ones, and how often, etc. This POINT SCORE would then appear
  in the Champs File(s) along with the other data.

- Using the same puzzle coding, have it opt to create a word grid puzzle,
  instead of a word search puzzle, where it would hide the words, then show
  you markers where letters of words are found and it would be up to the
  user to figure out which words went where, etc.

And from you...
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
    If you find any fault with this program, or have an idea NOT listed
above that you'd like to see implemented, please send them to me whenever
you get the chance.
@endnode
@Node CREATE "How to Create your OWN Puzzles in CNet Amiga Searcher?"
Creating Your Own Puzzles...
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
   To create additional puzzles for use with Searcher:

   If you can RUN Searcher, then:

        - If you have access to run the game itself, use the "C" command to 
          create the Title and Word List, making sure to answer YES to the 
          question it'll ask about saving the data to a text file. Once 
          finished, exit the game(or play the puzzle first), then reenter 
          the game. The SysOp holding ID # 1 will be asked if they wish to 
          process NEW puzzles. Your puzzle will then be added to the system.

   If you're NOT able to run Searcher directly, then:

        - Using any text editor, create a text file using this format:

            Line 1: The TITLE of your Puzzle. Use proper capitalization,
                    spelling, spacing, etc. so that it looks GOOD.

          Lines 2-: Starting on line 2, enter words, ONE PER LINE, that
                    you'd like to appear in the puzzle. There is no need
                    to attempt and format the words in any manner. Feel
                    free to use UPPER and lowercase, punctuation, spacing,
                    etc. whichever way is easiest for you. The only thing
                    to remember is that you specify ONE WORD PER LINE.

        - After finishing the text file, SAVE the file using a filename
          similar to the Title you specified on line 1, except MINUS any
          spacing, punctuation, etc. There is no limit on the LENGTH the
          filename can be, and you MAY use a combination of UPPER and
          lowercase letters. Here are some examples:

            - AFLFootballTeams  for the "AFL Football Teams" puzzle.
            - WOFSensations     for the "W. O. F. Sensations" puzzle.
            - ABBAHits          for the "A.B.B.A. Hits" puzzle.

        - When you get back to your bbs computer, copy this text file inside
          your "/Searcher/Puzzles/" directory, then RUN the Searcher program.
          It will "sense" the new puzzle and process it accordingly:

            - It's Title will be added to the !Puzzles and !Puzzles2 files.
            - The words will be cleaned up(stripped of spaces, punctuation,
              etc. and then converted to UPPERCASE).
            - The words will be sorted Longest to Shortest.
            - A new copy of the Puzzle will be written to disk using the
              2.00 format used by Searcher.

          You'll then see your puzzle listed in the menu upon completion!

============================================================================
